\pard\nowidctlpar {\cf0\f0 There\uc0{\u8217}s a lot of shouting in \uc0{\u201}douard Louis\uc0{\u8217} two short novels, The End of Eddy and History of Violence, and a lot of spit. The two often arrive conjoined, as if spit were the material form of language, a more reliable conveyor of meaning than the often misunderstood words. The End of Eddy opens with a schoolyard beating. \uc0{\u8220}The tall redhead spat in my face How do you like that, punk? The gob of spit dripped slowly down my cheek, thick and yellow, like the noisy mucus that obstructs the throats of old people or people who are ill.\uc0{\u8221} It\uc0{\u8217}s bracingly efficient. Between \uc0{\u8220}spat in my face\uc0{\u8221} and \uc0{\u8220}the gob of spit\uc0{\u8221} Louis embeds the words that the redhead spat out (italicized, as are all utterances of the book\uc0{\u8217}s working\uc0{\u173}class characters) so that nothing separates the spit from the words, a single material assault that cannot be wiped away.}\par
